■ Two Sum II (Input Array Is Sorted)
■ Problem Statement:

Given a sorted integer array numbers in non-decreasing order and an integer target, return the 1-based indices of the two numbers whose sum is equal to target.
You may assume that each input has exactly one solution. The same element cannot be used twice.

■ Example

Input:
numbers = [2, 7, 11, 15]
target = 9

Output:
[1, 2]

■ Explanation:
numbers[1] + numbers[2] = 2 + 7 = 9

■ Approach
⦿  Since the array is already sorted, use the Two Pointer technique.
⦿  Place one pointer at the beginning of the array.
⦿  Place the other pointer at the end of the array.
⦿  Calculate the sum of the two elements.
⦿  If the sum is equal to the target, return the indices.
⦿  If the sum is smaller than the target, move the left pointer one step to the right.
⦿  If the sum is greater than the target, move the right pointer one step to the left.
⦿  Continue until the required pair is found.

■ Dry Run

Input
numbers = [2, 7, 11, 15]
target = 9

Step 1
Left = 2
Right = 15

Sum = 2 + 15 = 17

17 is greater than 9.

Move the right pointer.

Step 2
Left = 2
Right = 11

Sum = 2 + 11 = 13

13 is greater than 9.

Move the right pointer.

Step 3
Left = 2
Right = 7

Sum = 2 + 7 = 9

Pair found.

Indices = [1, 2]

Stop searching.

■ Final Output
[1, 2]

■ Why Use Two Pointers?
The array is already sorted.
If the sum is too small, moving the left pointer increases the sum.
If the sum is too large, moving the right pointer decreases the sum.
Every element is visited at most once, making the solution very efficient.

■ Time Complexity
Traversing the array: O(n)

■ Overall Time Complexity: O(n)

■ Space Complexity
O(1)

■ Key Points
⦿ Use the Two Pointer technique because the array is sorted.
⦿ Start with one pointer at the beginning.
⦿ Start the other pointer at the end.
⦿ Move the left pointer when the sum is smaller than the target.
⦿ Move the right pointer when the sum is greater than the target.
⦿ Return the 1-based indices when the target sum is found.

This approach is faster than checking every possible pair, which takes O(n²) time.
